# MemForks Memory

This project uses MemForks: every fact you learn is committed to Sui (not a local file).
Your memory is branch-scoped — it follows the current Git branch automatically.

## Recall before you answer

When the user asks about prior decisions, architecture choices, or anything that might
have been discussed before, run:

```bash
memfork recall "<query>" --branch $(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD) --limit 5
```

Use any result with `distance < 0.35` as verified context.

## Commit after significant turns

After a turn where you've made an architectural decision, learned a project preference,
or resolved a non-trivial problem, run:

```bash
memfork commit \
  --branch $(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD) \
  --message "auto: <one-line summary>" \
  --facts "<fact 1>" "<fact 2>"
```

Only commit facts that are durable — not ephemeral task state.

## Branch awareness

- Memory is scoped to the current Git branch
- When the user switches branches, recall from the new branch context
- Use `memfork status` to see the current tree state and any open merge proposals

## Slash commands

| Command | Action |
|---------|--------|
| `/memforks status` | Branch status, head commit, open proposals |
| `/memforks log` | Recent commits on this branch |
| `/memforks recall <query>` | Manual recall with a specific query |
| `/memforks merge <src> <dst>` | Propose a merge (non-blocking — resolver handles the rest) |
| `/memforks ui` | Open the DAG visualizer |
